About the rules...

You can go on one adventure per day, which normally consists of a random monster fight (depending on the place you go) and grabbing the loot you find. For starters, I suggest you go to the sewers to fight the rats and ants.

As you level up, you gain +1 max HP, +1 max MP and a level up to a skill. You always gain the first skill (Optical Camouflage for humans) at level 2, the second skill at level 3, the third skill at level 4 and the ultimate skill (to be released when someone of that race beats the Mage Tower) at level 10, but you can only use the ultimate after beating the Mage Tower.

The stats listed on the Gdoc are only level 1 stats. Skills become much more powerful at higher levels, but they also consume more MP, unless passive.

Battle System

Note that this sounds complicated, but you'll get used to it after a few battles.

You start a battle after determining the order of actions. For example, if you and your teammate (T) encounter two monsters M1 and M2, you need to use RNG to get the order (more details at the RNG part).

Let's say the order is M1 > M2 > You > T. M1 would have an action first. Most monsters only have basic attacks, some have multiple hits per turn, some have special attacks and some even have spells. For each basic attack, you need to have a target roll, an accuracy roll and a damage roll. Target roll determines the target (You or T), accuracy roll determines whether it hits or misses, and damage roll determines the damage (meh). e.g. M1 has two hits with 1-4 damage each, so you need to roll TailsHeads2 for first hit and TailsTails3 for second hit. (default accuracy is 50%)

If a monster has special attacks or spells, there'll be a percentage shown in the Gdoc as its chance of using the special. e.g. if M2 has a special attack causing 3-8 damage with 30% usage rate and a normal attack of 1-4 damage, you need to roll 91 to determine whether it uses the special, Tails to determine the target, Heads4 for accuracy and damage if normal attack is used, 2 for damage if special is used (assume it can't miss).

Both you or T can roll the monster attacks. [sanemode] I'm sure the RNG doesn't favour anyone [/sanemode]

In your own turn, there can be three actions:
1. Consume a consumable (like drinking a potion or eating something)
2. Use any amount of non-turn-taking spells
3. Do a normal attack or use a turn-taking spell

You can do these in any order, e.g. you can start off attacking a monster, place an auto-turret (non-turn-taking), drink a HP potion, then cast a reflective shield (non-turn-taking).

After all the dice rolls/coin flips are done, you must wait for T to complete their turn.

These repeat until you both die or the monsters are both slain.

Death, Healing etc.

When you die (i.e. reaches 0HP or below), you're immediately withdrawn from wherever you're at, and sent to the local hospital where you regenerate all HP and MP, but lose all EXP you've gained this level. You also lose all process you've made towards a quest or an event, but you get to keep the loot you've found.

You can heal to full HP and MP when you level up.

The only other ways to heal are through consumables, or when you get lucky in a random event.

RNG

When you use the RNG in this forum, you need to be sure that it's fair, i.e. each possible outcome has equal chance to appear.

Coin Flip (Tails)
Heads means "No", "Miss" or 0
Tails means "Yes", "Hit" or 1
This can only be used if there are only two possible outcomes with 50% to occur each.

Other RNG (8 of HeartsM692414318IScissorsA)
For accuracy and chance rolls, low number means hit and high number means miss. e.g. if you roll a 70 with a 60% accuracy, you miss the attack. If you roll a 30 when a monster has 40% chance to use a special, it uses that special.

How to roll:
d3 - Scissors rocks = 1 paper = 2 scissors = 3 OR 1 (1,2 = 1) (3,4 = 2) (5,6 = 3)
d5 - E OR 4 (1,2 = 1) (3,4 = 2) (5,6 = 3) (7,8 = 4) (9,10 = 5)
d7 - G (There are 21 consonants and B,C,D are mapped to 1, F,G,H are mapped to 2 etc.)
d9 - 45 (There are 36 possible outcomes with two d6s, so you can always map 4 of them to 1)
d11 - Forget it, there's no way you can get this here
d13 - 6 of Clubs or T
d14 - (14 = 2x7, figure out the rest by yourself)

You can always try to combine some of the above to get larger numbers, e.g. you can get d130 by 5 of Spades1
